Thoughts on this system:

 20 different hash types randomly selected by validators (The number can of course change). This hash is only queried once every 100 seconds andthe miner has 5 seconds to reply, the miner will only know what to hash for once it is queried. Have the validators calculate the expected difficulty of the hash based on the system specs given by the validators. This prevents miners from constantly hashing as they will only know WHAT to hash for when they are queried.

@Fahd Khan

This will only reduce CPU power of the subnet by 5%. I believe this is a worthwhile change to stop this incredibly unsophisticated exploit.
If you have a POW system only, how could you rent processing power out to customers? Miners will have the incentive to only respond to the POW validation queries, and not do the other tasks

I think there are two issues - proof-of-work and securing the docker container

For POW, it may be necessary to do things like the following to get a true POW, not just an idle calculation: stess-ng, speedtext, https://github.com/wilicc/gpu-burn , https://github.com/NVIDIA/nccl-tests

For Securing the container, we need to ensure it has not been altered so that the POW can be trusted.  Things like a shared ssh key to get into the container, running something like tripwire in the container to store hashes of the important scripts and binaries and things  and to follow the container security best practices: https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Docker_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html.  It doesn't seem that there is a 100% way to lock down a container(see: https://forums.docker.com/t/lock-down-docker-image-container-so-that-nobody-can-see-whats-inside/85343) , but doing these things would help
